      "Heba turned to the girl. The girl's blue eyes came up from the floor slowly, the way a merchant raises a price, expecting to be beaten down.",
      "\"What are you called?\" Heba asked.",
      "\"Nahara,\" the girl said.",
      "Heba nodded once and offered nothing back, and was ashamed of the nothing, and offered it anyway.",
      "They climbed from the kitchens in a tired procession - Mata first, then the prince, then the merchant's daughter, then the girl from Ramek, then a jackal with flour on its nose. Matu and Nefer fell in behind them at the bend of the corridor, wearing the smug look of soldiers who had been right all along.",
      "The scribes' quarters sat on the palace's western side, where the incense thinned and the gold gave way to honest limestone. Nahara stopped at the third door and lifted the latch.",
      "Then her tray hit the floor.",
      "The clang ran down the hallway like a struck bell. Heba stepped past her, and the linen in her fist went hot as a coal.",
      "Sand lay across the threshold. Black sand, fine as ground pepper, poured with a careful hand. It spelled a single word in tall, patient letters.",
      "HEBA.",
      "And beneath the name, small and deliberate, the sand had drawn one more shape.",
      "A scale.",
      "Two plates. One feather. One heart.",
      "It was not the shape that emptied Heba's lungs. It was the hand. The letters leaned to the left, and the final stroke curled under itself like a cat's tail - the way one person in all of Kemet wrote her name.",
      "Her mother wrote it that way.",
      "Down in the dark beneath the palace, patient as dough, something began to rise."
