      "Mata swept Heba's name off the threshold with a broom made of river reeds, and she did it the way a priest handles a body.",
      "Every grain of black sand went into a clay jar. The jar was sealed with wax, wrapped in linen, and tied with a knot Heba had never seen a human hand make. When Nahara offered to fetch water to wash the stone, Mata said no. The stone would be scrubbed with salt, milk, and one word spoken backward.",
      "\"Was it my mother?\" Heba asked. \"Did she write it?\"",
      "\"Handwriting can be worn like a stolen dress,\" Mata said.",
      "\"That is not an answer.\"",
      "\"No,\" Mata agreed, and left with the jar under her arm.",
      "Heba slept badly. The room was clean and narrow, with two beds, one window, and a shelf where Nahara kept her belongings in a line so straight it could have been drawn with a ruler: a wooden comb, a folded map, a doll with no face. The doll bothered Heba until she remembered that in Ramek, faces were carved only after a child survived her fifth flood season.",
      "She never got her face, Heba thought, and turned toward the wall, and did not ask.",
      "Across the dark, the moth-heart fluttered half the night. Neither girl pretended better than the other.",
      "Morning arrived with drums.",
      "The hall of trials sat beneath the western temple, down forty steps that grew colder as they descended, as if the palace kept its winter in the basement. Torches lined the walls. The flames leaned away from the doorway at the bottom, which Heba chose not to think about.",
      "Eleven trainees stood in a line on the cold stone. Nine wore the white kilts of temple students, heads shaved, spines straight as reeds. The tenth was a broad girl from the river district who kept cracking her knuckles. The eleventh was Heba, in her beige gown, with braids to her waist and a folded strip of linen tucked against her ribs.",
      "The trial-master arrived the way rich men arrive - late, and pleased about it.",
      "His name was Userhat. He wore a leopard skin over one shoulder, and rings on eight of his ten fingers, and the expression of a man who had smelled something unfortunate many years ago and never recovered. A copper whistle hung from his neck on a cord of gold thread.",
      "\"Sorcery,\" Userhat announced, \"is not a gift. It is a debt. The gods lend. The body repays.\" He walked the line slowly, inspecting. \"Most of you will fail. Some of you will weep. One of you\" - his eyes found Heba's braids, her gown, her unpainted face, and made a small tour of all three - \"should perhaps be selling vegetables.\"",
      "The temple students laughed the way people laugh when a man with a whistle wants them to.",
      "Heba said nothing. In the market she had met a hundred Userhats. They squeezed the tomatoes, insulted the price, and always, always came back at closing time asking for a discount.",
      "Let him talk, she thought. Talk is free. Everything else, he will pay for.",
      "Userhat blew the whistle.",
      "The far wall opened. Beyond it lay a chamber the size of the marketplace, lit from above by a shaft of pale morning. The floor was sand. Smooth, golden, harmless-looking sand, raked into perfect lines like a scribe's fresh page.",
      "\"The chamber measures what you are made of,\" Userhat said. \"Cross it. Touch the far door. That is the whole of the trial.\" He smiled with the front of his face. \"The floor will decide what it thinks of you.\"",
      "\"What does that mean?\" the river-district girl asked.",
      "Userhat blew the whistle instead of answering, which told Heba everything she needed to know about him.",
      "The first student stepped onto the sand with his chin high. Ten paces in, his chin was still high, and the sand loved him for it - it firmed beneath his feet like packed clay. Fifteen paces. Twenty. Then a torch popped somewhere behind him, and his shoulders flinched, and the floor felt the flinch.",
      "The sand turned to water.",
      "He went down like a dropped spoon. The water swallowed him to the neck, then hardened into glass around his splashing, and the chamber held him there, sealed to the chin in a floor as clear as river ice, until two priests walked out with copper mallets and chipped him loose. He wept. Nobody laughed. Userhat made a note on a wax tablet with the tenderness of a tax collector.",
      "One by one, the chamber ate them.",
      "The floor turned to mud for the boastful boy and to knives of glass for the girl who moved too carefully, punishing her caution as if caution were a lie. For the seventh student, the sand became something pale and knobbled that Heba understood, after a moment, to be bone - ten thousand bones, shifting and rolling underfoot, and the boy's nerve went out of him like a lamp in wind, and the bones opened, and the priests had to go in with ropes.",
      "Three made it across. The river-district girl was one of them. She crossed the whole chamber cracking her knuckles, too stubborn to be afraid, and the sand stayed sand the entire way, bored by her.",
      "\"The merchant,\" Userhat said.",
      "Heba stepped to the edge.",
      "The sand lay flat and golden and patient. She could feel it paying attention. It had no heartbeat - she checked, out of new habit - but it had something. An appetite. A ledger. It was going to weigh her, and it was not going to be polite about the arithmetic.",
      "So it is a scale, Heba thought. Fine. I build those.",
      "She stepped on.",
      "Ten paces of sand. She kept her breath even, the way she did when a customer shouted, and the floor stayed sand, and she began - just barely - to hope.",
      "The floor felt the hope.",
      "Sand became water between one step and the next. Cold closed over her knees, her waist, her ribs, and panic came up her throat like a swallowed coin - and the water felt the panic and began to harden.",
      "No, she thought. No. Think. What is water?",
      "Water was the thing her mother hauled from the well every morning for thirty years. Water was weight. Water was two clay jugs on a shoulder pole, balanced, or you spilled both.",
