      "\"I wanted to come down,\" he said. \"Mata forbade it. She said the chamber grades on whose eyes you perform for.\"",
      "\"She was protecting my score.\"",
      "\"She was protecting your privacy.\" He saw her hands then. Something crossed his face, fast, like a fish under the surface. \"Sit.\"",
      "\"I can walk.\"",
      "\"You can also sit.\"",
      "There was a stone bench in the colonnade, worn smooth by a hundred years of tired novices. Heba sat because her knees voted for it before her pride could call a meeting. Ahmose knelt in front of her - a prince of Kemet, on the ground, in the open, as if the ground were furniture - and unrolled a strip of clean cotton from his sleeve with the ease of someone who had planned this.",
      "\"You carry bandages now?\" she asked.",
      "\"I had a feeling the floor would be rude.\"",
      "He took her left hand. He did not ask first, and she noticed that she had not needed him to, and she filed that away as a problem for later. His fingers were warm. The ink was still there, faint beneath his nails, sleeping. He cleaned the cuts with water from a small flask, and he was not delicate about it - he worked briskly, correctly, like a man who had bandaged real wounds and knew that gentleness came second to getting the grit out.",
      "That was the part that troubled her.",
      "Soft hands she could have dismissed. She had a shelf in her mind for princes with soft hands, right next to customers who squeezed the tomatoes. But he wrapped her palm the way her father wrapped a sprained wrist - snug at the base, looser at the knuckles, tied off where the knot would not rub - and there was no shelf for that, and she was too tired to build one.",
      "\"You crossed on your first attempt,\" he said. \"Do you know how rare that is?\"",
      "\"The floor and I understood each other. It is a scale. I have built worse.\"",
      "He laughed - one short, real note that echoed off the colonnade - and looked up at her, and the afternoon did something unnecessary with the gold in his eyes.",
      "Gentleness does not pay debt, she reminded herself. A wrapped hand is not a paid ledger. He is charming because charm is what princes make instead of bread.",
      "Her heart ignored the entire speech.",
      "\"Thank you,\" she said, and took her hand back, perhaps one breath later than strictly required.",
      "They came for her before dawn.",
      "Not the palace. The screaming did.",
      "Heba woke with Nahara already at the door, tray in hand - the girl slept beside that tray like a soldier beside a spear - and the two of them followed the sound through the scribes' corridor, down, and down again, to the long hall outside the royal library where the crocodile guards kept their night post.",
      "The boastful boy from the trial stood in the middle of the hall. The one the mud had taken. He was barefoot, in his sleeping linen, arms slack at his sides, facing the library doors.",
      "He was asleep. His eyes were open, and he was asleep. Heba could hear it - the slow, dreaming heart, wading through deep water.",
      "Around him, in a wide and careful circle, five armored crocodiles pressed themselves against the walls.",
      "Matu and Nefer, who had eaten a Greek in the marketplace at noon, who feared no king and answered no priest - they had backed against the limestone with their bellies low and their yellow eyes fixed on a sleeping boy, and they were making a sound Heba had never heard a crocodile make.",
      "They were whimpering.",
      "\"Wake him,\" a guard whispered. Nobody moved to do it.",
      "The boy's mouth opened.",
      "What came out was not the boy's voice, and it was not the baker's, and it was not a song. It was a dry sound, patient and pleased, like a page turning in an empty room.",
